The ﬁfth edition of this successful book provides comni'eiiezi

coverage of computer organization. It presents hardware design
principles and shows how hardware design is inﬂuenced by the
requirements of software. The book is suitable for undergraduate
electrical and computer engineering majors and computer science
specialists it is intended for use in a student's first course in

computer organization.

The material has been extensively rewritten to reﬂect the present

state of computer technology. Successful commercial processors
are used to illustrate the general concepts. ARM, 68000, and

Pentium processors serve as major architectural enemples. A
discussion ofembeddedsystems is also provided.

